ne(s[0]); // H\nConsole.WriteLine(s[4]); // o\n```\n\n---\n\n## Week 10: Methods\n\n### üìö Overview: Week 10 ‚Ä¢ Extra Practice\n\nSummary: # Week 10 Extra Practice: Mini models Pick **1‚Äì2** items (optional). - Make a Book class (Title, Author) with a constructor. - Make a Car class (Make, Model, Year) with a Describe() method. - Challenge: Add a method that returns a computed value (like AgeInYears() for a car). ## Open in Editor - Use...\n\n### üìù Homework: Week 10 ‚Ä¢ Week 10 Homework: Bank Account (tiny simulation)\n\nSummary: # Week 10 Homework: Bank Account (tiny simulation) ## Overview Create a BankAccount class and simulate deposits/withdrawals with simple rules. ## Requirements checklist (acceptance criteria) - [ ] Defines a BankAccount class with Owner and Balance - [ ] Constructor sets Owner and starting Balance - ...\n\n### üìö Overview: Week 10\nKey Concepts:\n- Focus:\n\nSummary: # Week 10 **Focus:** Classes & objects: modeling real things with code. ## This week‚Äôs pages - Lesson 1: [./lesson-1/](./lesson-1/) ‚Äî - Lesson 2: [./lesson-2/](./lesson-2/) ‚Äî - Extra practice: [./extra-practice/](./extra-practice/) ‚Äî - Lab: [./lab/](./lab/) ‚Äî - Homework: [./homework/](./homework/) ‚Äî...\n\n### üî¨ Lab: Week 10 ‚Ä¢ Week 10 Lab: Student Profile Class\n\nSummary: # Week 10 Lab: Student Profile Class ## Overview Create a Student class with properties and a method that returns a formatted summary string. ## Requirements checklist (acceptance criteria) - [ ] Defines a Student class with at least 3 properties (example: Id, Name, Major) - [ ] Includes a construct...\n\n### üìñ Lesson: Week 10 ‚Ä¢ Lesson 1\nKey Concepts:\n- Object\n- Property\n- 1) What‚Äôs the difference between a class and an object?\n\nSummary: # Week 10 Lesson 1: Classes = blueprints, objects = actual things ## Goal - Create a class with a few properties - Create objects from that class - Read and update property values ## What to know - **Class**: A blueprint that describes what something *has* and *can do*. - **Object**: A real instance...\n\nCode Example:\n```csharp\nclass Person\n{\n    public string Name { get; set; }\n    public int Age { get; set; }\n}\n\nPerson p = new Person();\np.Name = \"Ava\";\np.Age = 19;\n\nConsole.WriteLine($\"{p.Name} is {p.Age}.\");\n```\n\n### üìñ Lesson: Week 10 ‚Ä¢ Lesson 2\nKey Concepts:\n- Constructor\n- Default constructor\n- Parameterized constructor\n- 1) When does a constructor run?\n\nSummary: # Week 10 Lesson 2: Constructors (set up objects the easy way) ## Goal - Understand what a constructor does - Create a constructor with parameters - Use constructors to make cleaner code ## What to know - **Constructor**: A special method that runs when you create an object. - **Default constructor*...\n\nCode Example:\n```csharp\nclass Person\n{\n    public string Name { get; set; }\n    public int Age { get; set; }\n\n    public Person(string name, int age)\n    {\n        Name = name;\n        Age = age;\n    }\n}\n\nPerson p = new Person(\"Ava\", 19);\nConsole.WriteLine($\"{p.Name} is {p.Age}.\");\n```\n\n---\n\n## Week 11: Returning Values\n\n### üìö Overview: Week 11 ‚Ä¢ Extra Practice\n\nSummary: # Week 11 Extra Practice: Mini roster features Pick **1‚Äì2** items (optional). - Add a ‚Äòremove by ID‚Äô feature (search then remove). - Count how many students have names longer than 4 characters. - Challenge: Create a method FindById(List roster, string id) that returns a Student (or null). ## Open in...\n\n### üìù Homework: Week 11 ‚Ä¢ Week 11 Homework: Inventory Tracker (objects + list)\n\nSummary: # Week 11 Homework: Inventory Tracker (objects + list) ## Overview Create an Item class (Name, Quantity, maybe Price). Store items in a list and support at least one search or update. ## Requirements checklist (acceptance criteria) - [ ] Defines an Item class with at least 2 properties - [ ] Creates...\n\n### üìö Overview: Week 11\nKey Concepts:\n- Focus:\n\nSummary: # Week 11 **Focus:** Lists of objects